The transient photocurrent response and electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) of graphene QDs@MOF(Ti) based nanocomposite were further analyzed. Fig. 5(E) illustrates the photocurrent responses of the photocatalyst electrodes during on-off cycles under visible light irradiation. The graphene QDs@MOF(Ti) composite exhibited a significantly higher photocurrent response compared to MOF(Ti). Additionally, the photocurrent of graphene QDs@MOF(Ti) remained stable at 45 μA after six cycles, which is a 12% increase over MOF(Ti). Several factors contribute to the enhanced photocurrent observed. The integration of conductive graphene QDs with MOF(Ti) reduces the electrical resistance and impedance of the MOF(Ti), thereby accelerating the electron transfer rate and improving electron-hole (e−/h+) separation efficiency. Furthermore, the graphene QDs@MOF(Ti) composite demonstrated a substantial increase in light absorption, particularly in the visible light spectrum (Fig. 5(C)). The graphene QDs act as mediators for photogenerated charge separation and migration, facilitating the transfer of electrons from the conduction band (CB) of MOF(Ti) to the fluorine-doped tin oxide (FTO) substrate. This process reduces the recombination rate of e−/h+ pairs in graphene QDs@MOF(Ti), thereby enhancing the photoelectrochemical performance and resulting in higher photocurrent. To gain deeper insights into the charge transfer resistance and separation efficiency at the photocatalyst-electrolyte interface, EIS measurements were conducted, as shown in Fig. 5(F). The semicircle observed in the high-frequency range (105–103 Hz) represents the charge transfer resistance (R

                           ct
                        ), indicating the electron transfer between the electrode and the electrolyte. The arc radius of MOF(Ti) is almost indistinguishable, characteristic of electric double-layer capacitor (EDLC) materials. Conversely, the graphene QDs@MOF(Ti) composite exhibits a smaller arc radius than MOF(Ti), confirming more effective e−/h+ pair separation and rapid interfacial charge transfer in graphene QDs@MOF(Ti).
